<span id="freeTextContainer3186719018255778217">4.75 Stars - This is Lawrence Wright at his absolute best. Having red this prior to ’End of October’ &amp; that fiction was almost as brilliant but it’s foreshadowing is a large part of my admiration for it, this is just pure unadulterated filthy nonfiction greatness. <br/><br/>As all LW, the research is stunning &amp; akin to Caro in its thoroughness &amp; the ability of the writer to tell the story in the most concise yet chilling way possible.<br/><br/>The content is that which is close to all our hearts I’m sure, and a tim</span>
  <span id="freeText3186719018255778217" style="display:none">4.75 Stars - This is Lawrence Wright at his absolute best. Having red this prior to ’End of October’ &amp; that fiction was almost as brilliant but it’s foreshadowing is a large part of my admiration for it, this is just pure unadulterated filthy nonfiction greatness. <br /><br />As all LW, the research is stunning &amp; akin to Caro in its thoroughness &amp; the ability of the writer to tell the story in the most concise yet chilling way possible.<br /><br />The content is that which is close to all our hearts I’m sure, and a times it’s challenging not to rage-quit such is the detail given into some of the mistakes made by govt officials and agencies. But the book has a way of drawing your attention even when it’s on the table, it’s allure I found intoxicating at times much like 2020’s ‘Say Nothing’ by Patrick Radeon Keefe.<br /><br />Excellent read, a real gem &amp; one that’ll likely live on as a great of modern literature.</span>
