<div id="review_3643817540" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3643817540" />
    <a title="Joseph" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75236090-joseph"><img alt="Joseph" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559702033p2/75236090.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3643817540?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joseph" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joseph" href="/user/show/75236090-joseph">Joseph</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400030842" href="/book/show/525461.The_Looming_Tower">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3643817540" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7464275784477394364">The Pulitzer Prize winning effort from acclaimed historian Lawrence Wright, this book does not disappoint. We learn of the frustrating wall that existed that prevented cooperation between American intelligence organizations and the road that led to the terrorist attacks of 9/11. We learn more of Arab culture, both religious and secular, than in any book I&apos;ve read previously. Overall, this book belongs on the shelf along such works as Steve Coll&apos;s Ghost Wars and Directorate s, both fine studies o</span>
  <span id="freeText7464275784477394364" style="display:none">The Pulitzer Prize winning effort from acclaimed historian Lawrence Wright, this book does not disappoint. We learn of the frustrating wall that existed that prevented cooperation between American intelligence organizations and the road that led to the terrorist attacks of 9/11. We learn more of Arab culture, both religious and secular, than in any book I've read previously. Overall, this book belongs on the shelf along such works as Steve Coll's Ghost Wars and Directorate s, both fine studies on current world events. If you are looking for a book to snuggle up with this pandemic winter, make it this one.</span>
